The familial lineage of Jesus
This is the genealogy record of the family of Jesus Christ. He is the son of David. He is also the son of Abraham.
Abraham was the father of Isaac. Isaac was the father of Jacob. Jacob was the father of Judah and his brothers.
Judah was the father of Perez and Zerah. Tamar was their mother. Perez was the father of Hezron. Hezron was the father of Ram.
Ram was the father of Amminadab. Amminadab was the father of Nahshon. Nahshon was the father of Salmon.
Salem was Boaz's father. Rehab was Boaz's mother. Boaz was Obed's father. Ruth was Obed's mother. Obed was Jesse's father.
And Jesse was the father of King David. And David was the father of Solomon. And the mother of Solomon was the wife of Uriah.
Solomon was the father of Rehoboam. Rehoboam was the father of Abijah. Abijah was the father of Asa.
Asa was the father of Jehoshaphat. Jehoshaphat was the father of Jehoram. Jehoram was the father of Azariah.
Azariah was the father of Jotham. Jotham was the father of Ahaz. Ahaz was the father of Hezekiah.
Hezekiah was the father of Manasseh. Manasseh was the father of Amon. Amon was the father of Josiah.
Josiah was the father of Jeconiah and his brothers. At that time, the Jewish people were forced to go to Babylon.
After that, the family line continued. Jeconiah was the father of Shealtiel. And Shealtiel was the father of Zerubbabel.
Zerubbabel was the father of Abiud. Abiud was the father of Eliakim. Eliakim was the father of Azor.
Azor was the father of Sadok. Sadok was the father of Akim. Akim was the father of Eliud.
Eliud was the father of Eleazar. Eleazar was the father of Matthan. Matthan was the father of Jacob.
Jacob was the father of Joseph. Joseph was the husband of Mary. And Mary gave birth to Jesus, who is called the Messiah.
There were 14 generations from Abraham to David. There were 14 from David until the Jewish people were forced to go to Babylon. And there were 14 from that time to Christ. Jesus Christ was born.
This is how the birth of Jesus Christ happened. His mother Mary and Joseph had promised to marry. But before they began living together, it became clear that she would bear a child. She was pregnant by the power of the Holy Spirit.
Her husband, Yusuf, was a pious man. He did not want to expose her publicly. So he planned to divorce her quietly.
But while Joseph was thinking about this, the angel of the Lord appeared to him in a dream. The angel said, "Joseph, son of David, do not be afraid to take Mary home as your wife. The child conceived in her is from the Holy Spirit.
You will give birth to a son. You must name him Jesus. This is because he will save his people from their sins.
All this happened to fulfill what the Lord said would happen. He said it through the prophet,
"The virgin will conceive and give birth to a son, and will call him Immanuel." (Isaiah 7:14) The name Immanuel means "God with us."
Joseph woke up. He did as the angel of the Lord commanded him. He took Mary to his house as his wife.
But he did not consummate the marriage with her until she gave birth to a son. And Joseph named this name Jesus.
The Visit of the Wise Men to Jesus
Jesus was born in Bethlehem in Judah. This happened while Herod was king of Judah. After the birth of Jesus, wise men came from the East to Jerusalem.
They asked: "Where is the child who was born to be king over the Jews? When we were in the East, we saw his star. And now we have come to worship him."
When King Herod heard this, he was very disturbed. And everyone in Jerusalem was also troubled.
Herod summoned all the chief priests of the people. He also called the teachers of the law. And he asked them where the Messiah would be born.
"In Bethlehem in Judah," they answered. "This is what the prophet wrote. He said,
"And you, Bethlehem, land of Judah, are by no means least among the rulers of Judah. From you shall come a ruler who will shepherd my people Israel." (Micah 5:2)
Then Herod secretly summoned the wise men. He inquired precisely from them when the star had appeared.
Send them to Bethlehem. He said, "Go! Search carefully for the child. Once you find him, bring me a report. Then I can go and worship him too."
After the wise men listened to the king, they set off on their way. The star they saw when they were in the East moved ahead of them. And finally, it stopped above the place where the child was.
When they saw the star, they were filled with joy.
The wise men went to the house. There they saw the child with his mother Mary. They bowed down and worshiped him. Then they opened their treasures. They presented him with gold, frankincense, and myrrh.
But God warned them in a dream not to return to Herod. So they returned to their country by a different route. The flight of Jesus' family to Egypt
When the wise men left, Joseph dreamed. In the dream, the angel of the Lord appeared to him. The angel said: "Get up! Take the child and his mother and flee to Egypt. Stay there until I tell you to return. Herod will search for the child. He wants to kill him."
Youssef stood up. During the night, he left for Egypt with the child and his mother Mary.
They stayed there until King Herod died. Then what the Lord had said through the prophet was fulfilled: "Out of Egypt I called my son." (Hosea 11:1)
Herod realized that the wise men had deceived him. He became very angry. He issued orders concerning Bethlehem and the surrounding area. All boys aged two years or younger were to be killed. This corresponded to the time when the wise men saw the star.
In this way, the words spoken by the prophet Jeremiah were fulfilled. He said,
A voice is heard in Ramah. It is a voice of weeping and deep sorrow. Rachel is crying for her children. She refuses to be comforted, because they are gone. (Jeremiah 31:15) The return of Jesus' family to Nazareth
After the death of Herod, Joseph had a dream while he was still in Egypt. In the dream, the angel of the Lord appeared to him.
The angel said: "Get up! Take the child and his mother. Go to the land of Israel. Those who were trying to kill the child are dead."
So Joseph got up. He took the child and his mother Mary and returned to the land of Israel.
But he heard that Archelaus was king of Judea. Archelaus was ruling in place of his father Herod. This made Joseph afraid to go there. After being warned in a dream, Joseph returned to the land of Galilee instead.
There lived in a city called Nazareth. He fulfilled what the prophets said about Jesus. They said: "He will be called a Nazarene."
John the Baptist prepares the way
In those days, John the Baptist came and preached in the wilderness of Judea.
He said: "Repent of your sins! The kingdom of heaven has come near."
John is the one spoken of by the prophet Isaiah. He said: "A voice of one calling in the wilderness: Prepare the way for the Lord, make straight paths in the desert for him." (Isaiah 40:3)
