People came out to him from Jerusalem and all Judah. They also came from all the surrounding region of the Jordan River.
When they admitted that they had made a mistake, John baptized them in Jordan.
John saw many Pharisees and Sadducees coming to where he was baptizing. He said to them, "You brood of vipers! Who warned you to flee from the coming wrath of God?"
Bear fruit that shows you have turned away from your sins.
Do not think that you say to yourselves, "Abraham is our father." I tell you, God is able to raise up children for Abraham from these stones.
The axe is already at the roots of the trees. All trees that do not produce good fruit will be cut down. They will be thrown into the fire.
I baptize you with water, calling you to repent of your sins. But after me will come one who is more powerful than I, and I am not worthy to carry his sandals. He will baptize you with the Holy Spirit and fire.
He holds his spear in his hand to remove the straw from his plow. He will gather his wheat in the barn. But he will burn the straw with an unquenchable fire." Jesus baptizes
Jesus came from Galilee to the Jordan River. He wanted John to baptize him.
But John tried to stop him. He said to Jesus, "I need to be baptized by you. Why do you come to me?"
Jesus answered, "Let it be this way now. It is right for us to do this. It fulfills God's holy plan." Then John agreed.
As soon as Jesus was baptized, he came up out of the water. At that moment, the heavens opened. Jesus saw the Spirit of God descending on him like a dove.
A voice from heaven said, "This is my Son, whom I love. I am very pleased with him."
Jesus is tempted
The Holy Spirit led Jesus into the desert. There the devil tempted him.
After forty days and forty nights of fasting, Jesus was hungry.
The tempter came to him and said, "If you are the Son of God, tell these stones to become bread."
Jesus answered, "It is written: 'Man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that proceeds from the mouth of God.'" (Deuteronomy 8:3)
Then the devil took Jesus to the holy city. He made him stand on the highest point of the temple.
He said to him, "If you are the Son of God, throw yourself down. It is written: 'For he will command his angels concerning you to guard you in all your ways; they will lift you up in their hands, so that you will not strike your foot against a stone.'" (Psalm 91:11-12)
Jesus answered, "It is also written, 'Do not put the Lord your God to the test.'" (Deuteronomy 6:16)
Finally, the devil took Jesus to a very high mountain. He showed him all the kingdoms of the world and their glory.
He said: "If you fall down and prostrate to me, I will give you all of this."
Jesus said to him, "Away from me, Satan! It is written: 'Worship the Lord your God, and serve him only.'" (Deuteronomy 6:13)
Then the devil left Jesus. The angels came and took care of him. Jesus begins to preach.
John was imprisoned. When Jesus heard this, he returned to Galilee.
Jesus left Nazareth. He went to live in the city of Capernaum. It was located by the lake in the region of Zebulun and Naphtali.
And in this way, what the prophet Isaiah said was fulfilled. He said,
Land of Zebulun! Land of Naphtali! The Galilee, where non-Jews live! The land along the Mediterranean Sea! The lands east of the Jordan River!
"The people who live in darkness will see a great light. They now live in a very dark land. But a light will shine on them." (Isaiah 9:1, 2)
Since then, Jesus began to preach. He said, "Repent of your sins! The kingdom of heaven has come near." Jesus chooses the first disciples
One day, Jesus was walking beside the Sea of Galilee. There he saw two brothers. They were Simon Peter and his brother Andrew. They were casting a net into the lake. They were fishermen.
"Come. Follow me," Jesus said. "I will make you fishers of men."
So they left their nets and followed him immediately.
Advancing from there, he saw two other brothers. They were James son of Zebedee, and his brother John. They were in a boat with their father Zebedee. While they were preparing their nets, Jesus called them.
They immediately left the boat and their father and followed Jesus. Jesus heals the sick
Jesus went throughout all Galilee. There he taught in the synagogues. He preached the good news about the kingdom of God. He healed every disease and sickness that people were suffering from.
His news spread all over Syria. People brought to him all kinds of patients with different diseases. Some of them were suffering from severe pain. Others were possessed by demons. Some were trembling violently. Others could not move at all. And Jesus healed them all.
Large crowds followed him. Some people came from Galilee, from the region known as the Decapolis, and from Jerusalem and Judea. Others came from the region across the Jordan River.
Jesus grants blessings
Jesus saw the crowds. So he went up on the mountain and sat down. His disciples came to him.
Then he began to teach them. He said,
Blessed are the spiritually needy, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.
Blessed are those who mourn, for they shall be comforted.
Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth.
Blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they shall be satisfied.
Blessed are the merciful, for they shall be shown mercy.
Blessed are those whose hearts are pure. They will see God.
Blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall be called children of God.
Blessed are those who suffer for doing what is right. The kingdom of heaven is theirs.
Blessed are you when people insult you and persecute you and falsely say all kinds of evil against you because of me.
Rejoice and be glad. Your reward in heaven is great. In the same way, people harm the prophets who lived long ago. Salt and light
You are the salt of the earth. But suppose the salt loses its saltiness. How can its saltiness be restored? It is no longer good for anything. It will be thrown out. People will walk on it.
You are the light of the world. A city on a hill cannot be hidden.
Also, no one lights a lamp and puts it under a bowl. Instead, they put it on its stand. Then it gives light to everyone in the house.
In the same way, let your light shine before others. Then they will see the good works you do. And they will glorify your Father in heaven. Jesus gives the full meaning to the law.
Do not think that I have come to abolish the law or the prophets. I have not come to abolish, but to fulfill.
What I am about to tell you is the truth. Heaven and earth will pass away before the smallest letter of the law disappears. Not even the tiniest dot of the law will disappear until everything is accomplished.
Do not break even one of the least important commandments. And do not teach others to break them. If you do, you will be called the least important in the kingdom of heaven. Instead, practice these commandments and teach them. Then you will be called important in the kingdom of heaven.
Here is what I tell you. You must be more righteous than the Pharisees and the teachers of the law. If you are not, you will certainly not enter the kingdom of heaven. Murder
You have heard that it was said to those who lived long ago, "You shall not kill." (Exodus 20:13) Whoever kills will be judged for it.
But this is what I say to you. Do not be angry with your brother. Whoever is angry with his brother will be judged. And whoever says to his brother, "Raca," must stand before the Sanhedrin for judgment. But whoever says, "Fool!" will be in danger of the fire of hell.
Suppose you are offering your gift at the altar. And remember that your brother has something against you.
Leave your gift before the altar. First go and be reconciled with your brother. Then come back and offer your gift.
Suppose someone has a claim against you and takes you to court. Set the matter quickly. Do it while you are on the way with him. If you do not, he may hand you over to the judge. The judge may hand you over to the officer. And you may be thrown in jail.
What I will tell you is the truth. You will not leave until you pay the last penny! Adultery
You have heard that it was said, "You shall not commit adultery." (Exodus 20:14)
But I say to you, do not even look at a woman with a lustful gaze. For whoever looks at her in this way has already committed adultery with her in his heart.
If your right eye causes you to sin, pluck it out and throw it away. Your eye is only one part of your body. It is better to lose it than for your whole body to be thrown into the fire.
If your right hand tempts you to sin, cut it off and throw it away. Your hand is only one part of your body. It is better to lose it than for your whole body to be thrown into the fire. Divorce
It was said: "Suppose a man divorces his wife. If he does so, he must give her a certificate of divorce." (Deuteronomy 24:1)
But this is what I say to you. Whoever divorces his wife causes her to commit adultery. And whoever marries a divorced woman commits adultery. A man may not divorce his wife unless she is unfaithful to him. Oaths
Once again, you have heard what was said to your people long ago. They were told: "Do not break the covenants you made with the Lord. Keep the oaths you have sworn to Him."
But this is what I say to you. Do not make such promises at all. Do not make them in the name of heaven. That is the throne of God.
Do not make it in the name of the earth. That is the footstool of God. Do not make it in the name of Jerusalem. That is the city of the great King.
And do not swear by your heads. You cannot make a single hair white or black.
Let "yes" mean "yes." Let "no" mean "no." Anything beyond that is from the evil one. Be kind to others.
You have heard that it was said, "An eye for an eye, and a tooth for a tooth." (Exodus 21:24; Leviticus 24:20; Deuteronomy 19:21)
But this is what I tell you. Do not fight against an evil person. "Suppose someone strikes you on the right cheek. Then turn to him the other cheek also.
Suppose someone sues you to take your shirt. Let them take your coat as well.
Suppose someone forces you to walk one mile. Then walk with them two miles.
Give to whoever asks you for something. Do not refuse anyone who wants to borrow something from you. Love your enemies.
You have heard that it was said: "Love your neighbor. (Leviticus 19:18) And hate your enemy."
But this is what I tell you. Love your enemies. Pray for those who hurt you.
So you will be children of your Father who is in the heavens. "For He causes His sun to rise on the evil and the good, and sends rain on the righteous and the unrighteous.
If you love those who love you, what is your reward? Indeed, even sinners do that.
And if you only give life to your own people, what is your superiority over others? Do not the criminals do the same?
Be perfect, therefore, as your heavenly Father is perfect.
Giving to people in need
Beware of doing "good deeds" in front of others. Do not do them to be seen by others. If you do, your Father in heaven will not reward you.
When you give to the needy, do not announce it by blowing trumpets. Do not be like those who claim holiness only. They announce what they do in temples and in the streets. They want to be honored by others. What I will tell you is the truth. They have received their full reward.
When you give to the needy, do not let your left hand know what your right hand is doing.
So your giving will be secret. And your Father who sees in secret will reward you. Prayer
When you pray, do not be like those who only pretend to be holy. They love to stand and pray in the synagogues and on the street corners. They want others to see them. What I am telling you is true. They have received their full reward.
When you pray, go into your room. Close the door and pray to your Father who is unseen. And He will reward you. For your Father sees what is done in secret.
When you pray, do not keep on babbling like pagans do. They think they will be heard because of their many words.
Don't be like them. Your father knows what you need even before you ask him.
This is how you should pray. "Our Father who art in heaven, hallowed be thy name.
Let your kingdom come. Let what you want to happen on earth be done as it is in heaven.
Give us today our daily bread.
Forgive us our sins, as we also have forgiven those who have sinned against us.
Protect us from falling into sin when we are tempted. Save us from the evil one.
Forgive people when they wrong you. If you do so, your Father in heaven will also forgive you.
But if you do not forgive people their mistakes, your Father will not forgive your mistakes. Fasting
When you fast, do not look gloomy like those who only pretend to be pious. They make their faces very sad. They want to show people that they are fasting. What I am telling you is true. They have received their full reward.
But when you fast, put olive oil on your head. Wash your face.
Then no one else will know that you are fasting. Only your unseen Father will know. He will reward you. Your Father sees what is done in secret. Store up treasures in heaven.
Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth, where moth and rust destroy, and where thieves break in and steal.
But store up for yourselves treasures in heaven, where neither moth nor rust destroys, and where thieves do not break in or steal.
Your heart will be where your treasures are.
The eye is like a lamp for the body. Suppose your eyes are good. Then your whole body will be full of light.
But suppose your eyes are bad. Then your whole body will be filled with darkness. If the light inside you is darkness, then it will be very dark!
No one can serve two masters at the same time. He will hate one and love the other. Or he will be loyal to one and hate the other. You cannot serve both God and money at the same time. Do not worry.
I tell you, do not worry. Do not worry about your life and what you will eat or drink. And do not worry about your bodies and what you will wear. Is there not more to life than food? Are there not things more important to the body than clothing?
Look at the birds of the sky. They do not sow or reap. Nor do they gather grain into barns. But your Father in heaven feeds them. Are you not much more valuable than they?
Can you add just one hour to your life by worrying?
And why do you worry about clothes? Look at how the wildflowers grow. They do not work or make clothes.
But I tell you this: not even Solomon in all his glory was dressed like one of these flowers.
If God dresses the wild grass like this, won't He dress you even better? The grass here today, and tomorrow it is thrown into the fire. Your faith is very small!
So do not worry. And do not say: "What shall we eat?" or "What shall we drink?" or "What shall we wear?"
The people who do not fear God run after all those things. Your Father in heaven knows that you need them.
But seek first the kingdom of God. Do what you want to do. Then all those things will be given to you as well.
So do not worry about tomorrow. Tomorrow will worry about itself. Each day has enough trouble of its own.
Be fair when you judge others
Do not judge others. Then you will not be judged.
You will be judged by the same way you judge others. You will be measured by the same way you measure others.
You look at the sawdust in your friend's eye. But you do not pay attention to the piece of wood in your own eye.
How can you say to your friend: "Let me take the splinter out of your eye"? How can you say this while there is a piece of wood in your own eye?
O hypocrite! First, take the wooden plank out of your own eye. Then you will be able to see clearly to remove the speck of sawdust from your friend's eye.
Do not give what is holy to dogs. Do not throw your pearls to pigs. If you do, they may trample them under their feet. Then they may turn and tear you to pieces. Ask, seek, knock.
Ask and it will be given to you. Seek and you will find. Knock and the door will be opened to you.
Everyone who asks will be given. Whoever seeks will find. The door will be opened to those who knock.
If your son asks you for bread, which of you will give him a stone?
Or suppose he asked for a fish. Which of you would give him a snake?
And if you, being evil, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your Father in heaven give good gifts to those who ask Him!
In everything, treat others as you would like to be treated. This is what is written in the law and the prophets. The great and small gates
Enter the kingdom of God through the narrow gate. The gate is wide and the road is broad that lead to death and hell. Many people walk that road.
But the gate is narrow and the way that leads to life is narrow. Few find it. A tree and its fruit
Beware of false prophets. They come to you pretending to be sheep. But inside, they are hungry wolves.
You can know their true nature by what they do. Do people pick grapes from thornbushes? Do they pick figs from thistles?
In the same way, every good tree bears good fruit. But the bad tree bears bad fruit.
A good tree does not bear bad fruit. And a bad tree does not bear good fruit.
Every tree that does not bear good fruit is cut down. It is thrown into the fire.
You can know every tree by its fruit.
Not everyone who says to me, "Lord, Lord," will enter the kingdom of heaven, but only the one who does the will of my Father who is in heaven will enter.
Many will say to me on that day, "Lord! Lord! Did we not prophesy in your name? Did we not cast out demons in your name? Did we not do many miracles in your name?"
Then I will say to them plainly, "I never knew you. Away from me, you evildoers!" The wise and foolish builders
"Therefore, everyone who hears these words of mine and puts them into practice is like a wise man who built his house on the rock."
The rain comes. The water rises. The winds blow and strike that house. But it does not fall. It is built on the rock.
But everyone who hears my words and does not put them into practice is like a foolish man who built his house on the sand.
The rain comes. The water rises. The winds blow and hit that house. And it falls with a loud noise.
Jesus finished saying all these things. The crowd was amazed at his teaching.
He taught as one who had authority. He did not speak like their teachers of the law.
Jesus heals a man who was suffering from a skin disease
Jesus came down from the side of the mountain. Large crowds followed him.
A man who was suffering from a skin disease came and knelt before Jesus. He said, "Lord, if you are willing, you can make me clean."
Jesus reached out his hand and touched the man. He said, "I am willing to do this." "Be clean!" Immediately the man was healed of his skin disease.
Then Jesus said to him, "Do not tell anyone. Go, show yourself to the priest. Offer the gift that Moses commanded. It will be a testimony to them." A Roman centurion believes
When Jesus entered Capernaum, a Roman officer came to him. He asked Jesus for help.
He said: "O Lord, my servant lies in the house and cannot move. He is suffering greatly."
Jesus said, "I will go and heal him."
The commander answered: "Lord, I am not worthy that you should enter under my roof. But just say the word, and my servant will be healed."
I myself am a man under authority. And I have soldiers who obey my orders. I say to this one: "Go," and he goes. I say to that one: "Come," and he comes. I say to my servant: "Do this," and he does it.
When Jesus heard this, he was amazed. He said to those who were following him, "What I am about to tell you is true. I have not found anyone in Israel with faith as strong as this."
I tell you that many will come from the east and the west. They will take their places at the feast in the kingdom of heaven. They will sit with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.
As for those who think they belong to the kingdom, they will be cast out into the darkness. There they will weep and gnash their teeth."
Then Jesus said to the Roman officer: "Go! It will be done as you have believed." And his servant was healed at that very hour. Jesus heals many people
When Jesus entered Peter's house, he saw his mother-in-law. She was lying on the bed. She was suffering from a fever.
Jesus touched her hand, and the fever left her. She got up and began to serve him.
When evening came, many people who were possessed by demons were brought to Jesus. He cast out the spirits with a word. He healed all the sick.
He did this to fulfill what the prophet Isaiah said. He said: "Surely he took up our pain and bore our suffering. We considered him punished by God, stricken by him, and afflicted. But he was pierced for our transgressions, he was crushed for our iniquities." (Isaiah 53:4) The cost of following Jesus
Jesus saw the crowd around him. So he commanded his disciples to go to the other side of the Sea of Galilee.
Then the teacher of Sharia came to him and said: "O teacher, I will follow you wherever you go."
Jesus answered, "Foxes have dens, and birds of the sky have nests, but the Son of Man has no place to lay his head."
And another follower said to him, "Lord, let me first go and bury my father."
But Jesus said to him, "Follow me. Let the dead bury their own dead." Jesus calms the storm
Jesus got into the boat. His disciples followed him.
Suddenly, a terrible storm blew over the lake. The waves crashed over the boat. But Jesus was sleeping.
The students went and woke him up. They said, "Lord! Save us! We are about to drown!"
He answered, "Your faith is so small! Why are you so afraid?" Then Jesus got up and commanded the winds and the waves to stop. The weather became completely calm.
The students were amazed. They asked, "Who is this man that even the winds and the waves obey him?" Jesus heals two men possessed by demons.
Jesus arrived at the other side of the lake in the region of the Gadarenes. He was met by two men possessed by demons. They came out of the tombs. The two men were so fierce that no one could pass that way.
"Son of God, what do you want from us?" they shouted. "Have you come here to punish us before our time of judgment?"
Not far away, a large herd of pigs was grazing.
The demons appealed to Jesus, "If you cast us out, send us into the herd of pigs."
Jesus said to them, "Go!" So the demons came out of the men and entered the pigs. The whole herd rushed down the steep slope. They ran into the lake and drowned in the water.
The ones who were tending the pigs fled. They entered the city and informed everyone of all this. They told the people what had happened to the men who had been possessed by demons.
Then the whole city went out to meet Jesus. And when they saw him, they begged him to leave their region.
Jesus heals a man who could not walk
Jesus got into the boat. He crossed to the other side of the lake and arrived at his town.
Some men brought to him a man who could not walk. He was lying on a mat. Jesus saw their faith. He said to the man, "Do not lose hope, my son. Your sins are forgiven."
Then some of the teachers of Sharia said to themselves: "This man is saying something very evil!"
Jesus knew what they were thinking. He said, "Why do you harbor evil thoughts in your hearts?"
Is it easier to say: "Your sins are forgiven"? Or to say: "Get up and walk"?
I want you to know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins." Then he said to the man who could not walk: "Get up," he said. "Take your mat and go home."
The man stood up and went home.
