One day the disciples of John came. They said to Jesus, "We and the Pharisees fast. Why do your disciples not fast?"
Jesus answered, "How can the guests of the bridegroom be sad while he is with them? The time will come when the bridegroom will be taken away from them. Then they will fast.
People do not sew a new piece of cloth onto old clothes. The new piece will separate from the old one. That will make the tear worse.
"No one pours new wine into old wineskins. If they do, the skins will burst. The wine will run out, and the skins will be ruined. No, they pour new wine into new wineskins. Then both are preserved." A dead girl and a suffering woman
While Jesus was saying this, a ruler came. He knelt on his knees before Jesus. He said, "My daughter has just died. But come and lay your hand on her. Then she will live again."
Jesus got up and went with him. Likewise, his disciples.
At that moment, a woman came from behind Jesus. She was suffering from a disease that caused her to bleed. It had lasted for 12 years. She touched the hem of his garment.
I thought, "All I need is to touch his clothes. Then I will be healed."
Jesus turned and saw her. He said, "Dear woman, do not lose hope. Your faith has healed you." And the woman was healed at that very moment.
When Jesus entered the ruler's house, he saw the flute players there. And he saw the noisy crowd.
He said: "Go. The girl is not dead. She is sleeping." But they laughed at him.
After the crowd was sent outside, Jesus entered. He took the girl's hand, and she got up.
News about what Jesus did spread throughout the whole region. Jesus heals two blind men.
As Jesus was going from there, two blind men followed him. They called out, saying, "Have mercy on us, Son of David!"
When Jesus went indoors, the blind men came to him. He asked them, "Do you believe that I am able to do this?" They answered him, "Yes, Lord."
Then he touched their eyes. He said, "It will happen to you as you have believed."
They could now see again. Jesus warned them sternly, saying, "Make sure that no one knows about this."
But they went out and spread the news. They talked about it all over that region.
As they were going out, another man was brought to Jesus. A demon controlled him, so he could not speak.
When the devil was cast out, the man spoke. The crowd was amazed. They said, "Nothing like this has ever been seen in Israel before."
But the Pharisees said, "He casts out demons by the power of the prince of demons." There are only a few workers.
Jesus was going through all the towns and villages. He was teaching in their synagogues. He was preaching the good news about the kingdom. And he was healing every disease and sickness.
When he saw the crowds, he felt deep concern for them. They were exhausted and helpless, like sheep without a shepherd.
Then Jesus said to his disciples: "The harvest is plentiful, but the workers are few."
So ask the Lord of the harvest to send out workers into his harvest field.
Jesus Sends the Twelve Disciples
Jesus called his twelve disciples to come to him. He gave them the authority to cast out evil spirits and to heal every disease and sickness.
Here are the names of the twelve apostles. The first is Simon Peter and his brother Andrew. Then comes James son of Zebedee and his brother John.
Next are Philip and Bartholomew, as well as Thomas and Matthew the tax collector. There are also two others, James son of Alphaeus and Thaddaeus.
The latter two are Simon the Zealot and Judas Iscariot. Judas is the one who would later betray Jesus to his enemies.
Jesus sent these twelve with the following orders. He said: "Do not go among the Gentiles." "Do not enter any city of the Samaritans."
Rather, go to the Children of Israel. They are like sheep who have gone astray.
And as you walk, proclaim this message: "The kingdom of heaven is near."
Heal the sick. Raise the dead. Cleanse those who have leprosy. Drive out demons. You have received freely; give freely.
Do not take gold or silver or copper in your belts.
Do not take a bag for the trip. Do not take extra clothes, sandals, or walking sticks. The worker should be given what he needs.
When you enter a city or village, look for someone willing to welcome you. Stay at that person's house until you leave.
When you enter the house, greet those who live in it.
If that house welcomes you, grant it the blessing of peace. And if it does not, do not bless it.
Some people may not welcome you or listen to your words. And if they don't, shake the dust off your feet when you leave that house or city.
What I will tell you is the truth. On the Day of Judgment, the condition of Sodom and Gomorrah will be easier than the condition of that city.
I am sending you out like sheep among wolves. Therefore, be as shrewd as snakes and as innocent as doves.
Beware! The men will hand you over to the local courts. They will flog you in their temples.
You will be brought before governors and kings because of me. You will be witnesses to them and to those who are not Jews.
But when they arrest you, do not worry about what you will say or how you will say it. At that time, the right words will be given to you to say.
You will not be the speaker. Your father's spirit will speak through you.
Brothers will hand over their brothers to be killed. Fathers will hand over their children. Children will attack their fathers and execute them.
Everyone will hate you because of me. But those who persevere until the end will survive.
When people attack you in one place, flee to another place. What I am about to tell you is true. You will not finish going through the cities of Israel before the Son of Man comes.
The student is not better than his teacher. The servant is not better than his master.
It is enough for the student to be like his teacher. And it is enough for the servant to be like his master. If the master of the house is called Beelzebub, what can the others who live there expect?
So do not fear your enemies. Everything secret will be revealed publicly. Everything hidden will be shown.
What I tell you in the dark, speak it in the daylight. What is whispered in your ear, shout it from the rooftops.
Do not fear those who kill the body but cannot kill the soul. Rather, fear Him who can destroy both soul and body in hell.
Are not two sparrows sold for only one falus? Yet not one of them falls to the ground without your Father knowing it.
He even counts every hair on your head!
So do not be afraid. You are more valuable than many sparrows.
What about someone who says before others that he knows me? I will also say before my Father in heaven that I know him.
But what about a person who says in front of others that he does not know me? I will say before my Father in heaven that I do not know him.
Do not think that I have come to bring peace to the earth. I did not come to bring peace. I came to bring the sword.
I have come to turn "children against their parents. Daughters will refuse to obey their mothers. And they will be against their mothers-in-law.
"Enemies of a man are members of his own household." (Micah 7:6)
Whoever loves his father or mother more than me does not deserve me. Whoever loves his son or daughter more than me does not deserve me.
And whoever does not carry his cross and follow me is not worthy of me.
If anyone finds their life, they will lose it. But if anyone loses their life for my sake, they will find it.
Whoever accepts you accepts me. And whoever accepts me accepts the one who sent me.
Suppose a person welcomes a prophet as a prophet. That person will receive the reward of the prophet. And suppose a person welcomes a pious person as a pious person. That person will receive the reward of the pious person.
Suppose someone even gave a cup of cold water to a child following me. What I will tell you is the truth. That person will definitely be rewarded.
Jesus and John the Baptist
Jesus finished teaching His twelve disciples. Then He continued teaching and preaching in the cities of Galilee.
John was in prison. When he heard what Christ was doing, he sent his disciples to him.
They asked him, Jesus, "Are you the one who was to come, or should we look for someone else?"
Jesus answered, "Go back to John. Tell him what you hear and see.
The blind regain their sight. The disabled walk. Skin patients are healed. The deaf hear. The dead are brought back to life. And the good news is proclaimed to the poor.
Blessed are those who do not abandon their faith for my sake.
While John's disciples were leaving, Jesus began to speak to the crowd about John. He said, "What did you go out to see in the wilderness? Tall grass waving in the wind?"
If not, then what did you come out to see? A man wearing fancy clothes? No. People who wear fancy clothes are in the palaces of kings.
So what did you come out to see? A prophet? Yes, I tell you, and more than a prophet.
He is the one who is written about in the Holy Bible. It says: "Behold, I send my messenger before your face, who will prepare your way before you." (Malachi 3:1)
What I will tell you is the truth. No one born is greater than John the Baptist. But the least important person in the kingdom of heaven is more important than him.
Since the days of John the Baptist, the kingdom of heaven has been advancing with power. And the strong men seize it.
All the prophets and the law prophesied until John came.
If you are willing to accept it, John is Elijah who was supposed to come.
Whoever has an ear, let him hear.
What can I compare the people of today to? They are like children sitting in the markets calling out to others. They say,
We played the flute for you, but you did not dance. We sang a funeral hymn, but you did not grieve.
When John came, he neither ate nor drank as you do. And people say, "He is possessed by a demon."
But when the Son of Man came, he ate and drank just as you do. And people say, "This man eats and drinks too much. He is a friend of tax collectors and sinners." Those who act wisely prove that wisdom is right. Cities that do not turn away from sin
Jesus began to speak against the cities where he had performed most of his miracles. The people there did not repent of their sins. So he said,
Woe to you, Chorazin! Woe to you, Bethsaida! If the miracles that were performed in you had been performed in Tyre and Sidon, they would have repented long ago in sackcloth and ashes. But they have worn sackcloth and sat in ashes.
But I say to you this. On the Day of Judgment, the condition of Tyre and Sidon will be easier than your condition.
And what about you, Capernaum? Will you be raised to the sky? No! You will go down to the place of the dead. Suppose the miracles that happened in you had happened in Sodom. It would still exist today.
But I tell you this. On the Day of Judgment, the condition of Sodom will be easier than your condition." Rest for everyone who is weary
At that time Jesus said, "I thank you, Father. You are the Lord of heaven and earth. You have hidden these things from the wise and learned. But you have revealed them to little children.
Yes, Dad. This is what I wanted.
The father gave me everything. The father is the only one who knows the son. And the only ones who know the father are the son and those whom the son chooses to let know him.
Come to me, all you who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest.
Be my servants and learn from me. I am gentle and humble in heart. You will find rest for your souls.
My service is easy, and my load is light.
Jesus is the Lord of the Sabbath day
On a Saturday, Jesus was walking through the grain fields. His disciples were hungry. So they began to pick some heads of grain and eat them.
The Pharisees saw this. They said to Jesus, "Look! It is against the law to do this on the Sabbath. But your disciples do it anyway!"
Jesus answered, "Have you not read what David did? He and his men were hungry.
So he entered the house of God. He and his men ate the sacred bread. It was only allowed for the priests to eat it.
Have you not read the law? It tells how the priests in the temple should perform their work every Sabbath day. But they are not considered guilty.
I tell you that there is one here who is greater than the temple.
The writings say, "I desire mercy, not sacrifice." (Hosea 6:6) You do not know what these words mean. If you did, you would not accuse those who are innocent.
The Son of Man is Lord of the Sabbath.
Starting from that place, Jesus entered their synagogue.
There was a man with a weak and crooked hand. The Pharisees were trying to find fault with Jesus. So they asked him, "Is it lawful for us to heal on the Sabbath?"
He said to them: "What if one of your sheep falls into a pit on the Sabbath? Would you not hold it and lift it out?
Man is nobler than sheep! Therefore, the law allows us to do good on the Sabbath.
Then Jesus said to the man, "Stretch out your hand." So he stretched it out, and it was as good as new, as good as the other hand.
But the Pharisees went out and conspired on how to kill Jesus. The chosen servant of God
Jesus knew everything about the Pharisees' plans. So he left that place. Many followed him, and he healed all their sick.
But he warned them not to tell who he was.
That was to fulfill what was spoken by the prophet Isaiah. He says,
Here is my servant. I have chosen him. He is the one I love. I am very pleased with him. I will put my spirit upon him. He will proclaim to the nations that everything will be restored.
He will not argue or shout. No one will hear his voice in the streets.
He will not break a bent branch. He will not extinguish a flame whose light is fading. He will make everything alright.
"The peoples will put their hope in him." (Isaiah 42:1-4) Jesus and Beelzebub
A man possessed by demons was brought to Jesus. The man was blind and could not speak. Jesus healed this man. Then the man was able to speak and see.
All the people were amazed. They said, "Could this be the son of David?"
When the Pharisees heard this, they said, "This man drives out demons by the power of Beelzebul, the prince of demons."
Jesus knew what they were thinking. He said to them, "Every kingdom divided against itself will be ruined. And every city or family divided against itself will not stand."
If the devil drives out a devil, he is fighting against himself. So how can his kingdom stand?
She says that I cast out demons by the power of Beelzebul. So by whose power do your people cast out demons then? Then they will be your judges.
But if I cast out demons by the Spirit of God, then the kingdom of God has come upon you.
Or think about this. How can you enter the house of a strong man and take what he owns just like that? You must first restrain him. Then you can steal his house.
Whoever is not with me is against me. And whoever does not gather the sheep with me scatters them.
So I tell you this: Every sin and every evil word spoken against God will be forgiven. But saying evil things against the Holy Spirit will not be forgiven.
Whoever speaks a word against the Son of Man will be forgiven. But whoever speaks against the Holy Spirit will not be forgiven. That person will not be forgiven, neither now nor in the days to come.
If you make the tree good, its fruit will be good. If you make the tree bad, its fruit will be bad. You can know the tree by its fruit.
O nests of poisonous snakes! How can you wicked ones say anything good? Your mouths speak all that is in your hearts.
The good man says good things. These come from the goodness stored inside him. The evil man says evil things. These come from the evil stored inside him.
But this is what I tell you. On the Day of Judgment, people will be held accountable for every reckless word they have spoken.
"With your words, you will be condemned or acquitted." The miraculous sign of Yunus
Some of the Pharisees and teachers of the law came to Jesus. They said, "Teacher, we want to see a miraculous sign from you."
He answered: "Evil and untrustworthy people seek a miraculous sign! But only the sign of the Prophet Jonah will be given.
Jonah was in the belly of a great fish for three days and three nights. Something similar will happen to the Son of Man. He will spend three days and three nights in the grave.
The men of Nineveh will stand on the Day of Judgment with the people who live now. The people of Nineveh will prove that these people are guilty. The men of Nineveh turned away from their sins when Jonah preached to them. And now there is someone greater than Jonah.
The Queen of the South will stand on the Day of Judgment with the people who are living now. And she will prove that they are guilty. She came from a very distant place to listen to the wisdom of Solomon. And now there is someone greater than Solomon here.
What happens when an evil spirit leaves a person? It passes through dry regions searching for a place to rest. But it does not find one.
Then he says, "I will return to the house I left." And when he arrives there, he finds the house empty. The house has been cleaned and tidied.
Then the evil spirit goes out and takes with it seven other evil spirits more wicked than itself. They enter and dwell there. The condition of that man becomes worse than before. This is how the fate of the wicked will be in this time." The mother of Jesus and His brothers
While Jesus was still speaking to the crowd, his mother and brothers stood outside. They wanted to speak to him.
Someone said to him: "Your mother and siblings are standing outside. They want to talk to you."
Jesus answered him, "Who is my mother? And who are my brothers?"
Jesus pointed to his disciples. He said, "This is my mother! These are my brothers!"
Whoever does the will of my Father in heaven is my brother or sister or mother.
The Farmer's Story
On that same day, Jesus went out of the house and sat by the Sea of Galilee.
A large crowd gathered around him. So he boarded a boat. He sat in it. All the people stood on the shore.
Then he told them many things using stories. He said: "A farmer went out to sow his seed.
Scattering the seeds on the ground. Some fell on the road. The birds came and ate them.
Some seeds fell on rocky places, where there was not much soil. The plants sprouted quickly because the soil was not deep.
When the sun rose, it burned the plants. They dried up because they had no roots.
And some seeds fell among the thorns. The thorns grew and the plants became crowded.
And other seeds fell on good soil. So they produced a crop a hundred, sixty, or thirty times what was sown.
Whoever has ears, let them hear.
The disciples came to him. They asked, "Why do you use stories when you speak to people?"
He answered: "I have been given the opportunity to understand the secrets of the kingdom of heaven. They were not given to outsiders.
Everyone who has this kind of knowledge will be given more. Indeed, they will have very much. And whoever does not have this kind of knowledge, even what little they have will be taken from them.
Here is why I use stories when I talk to people. I say: "They look, but they don't really see. They listen, but they don't truly hear or understand.
In them, the words of the prophet Isaiah are fulfilled. He said: "You will hear but never understand. You will see but never know what you are seeing."
The hearts of these people have grown hard. They barely hear with their ears. They have closed their eyes. Otherwise, they might see with their eyes. They might hear with their ears. They might understand with their hearts. They might return to the Lord, then He will heal them. (Isaiah 6:9, 10)
But blessed are your eyes because they see. And blessed are your ears because they hear.
What I am going to tell you is the truth. Many prophets and righteous people wanted to see what you see. But they did not see it. They wanted to hear what you hear. But they did not hear it.
Listen! This is the meaning of the farmer's story.
People hear the message about the kingdom but do not understand it. Then the evil one comes. He steals what was sown in their hearts. These people are like the seed sown along the path.
As for those on whom the seeds that fell on the rocky ground were sown, they are the ones who hear the word and immediately rejoice.
But they have no roots. Therefore, they only last for a short time. They quickly fall away from the faith when hardships or suffering come because of the message.
As for those who fell among the thorns, they are the ones who hear the word, but the worries of this life and the deceitfulness of wealth choke it, so it does not bear fruit.
But others received the seed that fell on good soil. They are the ones who hear the message and understand it. They produce a crop a hundred, sixty, or thirty times what the farmer planted." The Parable of the Weeds
Jesus told the crowd another story. "This is what the kingdom of heaven is like," he said. "A man planted good seeds in his field.
But while everyone was asleep, his enemy came. The enemy planted weeds among the wheat and then left.
The wheat began to grow and form grains. At the same time, weeds appeared.
The owner's servants came to him. They said, "O master, did you not sow good seeds in your field? So how then did the weeds grow?"
He said, "That was done by an enemy." The servants asked him, "Do you want us to go and uproot the weeds?"
"No," the owner replied. "While you are pulling out the weeds, you might pull out the wheat as well."
"Let both of them grow together until the harvest. And at that time I will tell the workers what to do. This is what I will say to them: First, gather the weeds and bind them in bundles to be burned. Then gather the wheat and bring it into my barn." The Parables of the Mustard Seed and the Yeast
Jesus told the crowd another story. He said, "The kingdom of heaven is like a mustard seed. Someone took the seed and planted it in a field.
It is the smallest of all your seeds. But when it grows, it becomes the largest plant in the entire garden. It becomes a tree. Birds come and rest on its branches.
Jesus told them another story. He said: "The kingdom of heaven is like yeast," "a woman mixed it into a large amount of flour. The yeast spread through all the dough."
Jesus spoke to the crowds about all these things using stories. He did not say anything to them without telling a story.
So the words spoken by the Prophet were true. He said: "I will open my mouth with a parable; I will declare dark sayings from of old. I will speak of things that have been hidden since the creation of the world." (Psalm 78:2) Jesus explains the story of the harmful weed.
Then Jesus left the crowd and went into the house. His disciples came to him. They said, "Explain to us the story of the weeds in the field."
He answered, "The one who sowed the good seed is the Son of Man.
The field is the world. The good seed represents the people who belong to the kingdom. The weeds are the people who belong to the evil one.
The enemy who sows them is the devil. The harvest is the Day of Judgment. And the workers are the angels.
Weeds are uprooted and burned in the fire. This is how it will be on the Day of Judgment.
The Son of Man will send his angels. They will uproot from his kingdom everything that causes sin. They will also destroy everyone who does evil.
They will be thrown into the blazing furnace. There they will weep and gnash their teeth.
Then the people of God will shine like the sun in the kingdom of their Father. He who has ears, let him hear. The stories of the hidden treasure and the pearl
The kingdom of heaven is like a hidden treasure in a field. When a man found it, he hid it again. He was very happy. So he went and sold everything he had. And bought that field.
Once again, the kingdom of heaven is like a merchant seeking fine pearls.
He found one that was very precious. So he went and sold everything he owned. And he bought that pearl. The Parable of the Pearl
Again, the kingdom of heaven is like a net. It was pulled to the shore. It caught all kinds of fish.
When it was full, the fishermen pulled the net to the shore. Then they sat down and gathered the good fish into baskets. But they threw the bad fish away.
This is how it will be on the Day of Judgment. The angels will come. They will separate the people who did what was wrong from those who did what was right.
The wicked will be thrown into the blazing furnace. There the wicked will weep and gnash their teeth.
Jesus asked, "Do you understand all these things?" They answered, "Yes."
He said to them: "Every teacher of the law who has been instructed about the kingdom of heaven is like the owner of a house who brings out of his storeroom new treasures as well as old." A prophet without honor
Jesus finished telling these stories. Then he moved on from there.
He came to his hometown, Nazareth. There he began to teach the people in their synagogue. They were amazed. "Where did this man get this wisdom? And where did he get this power to perform miracles?" they asked.
Isn't this the son of the carpenter? Isn't his mother's name Mary? Aren't his brothers Jacob, Joseph, Simon, and Judah?
Aren't all his sisters with us? Then where did this man get all these things from?
They were not pleased with him at all. But Jesus said to them, "A prophet is not honored in his hometown. He receives no honor in his own house."
He only performed some miracles there because they did not have faith.
The head of John the Baptist is severed.
At that time, Herod, the ruler of Galilee and Perea, heard reports about Jesus.
He said to his attendants: "This is John the Baptist. He has risen from the dead! That is why he has the power to perform miracles."
Herod had arrested John. He bound him and put him in prison because of Herodias. She was the wife of Philip, Herod's brother.
John was saying to Herod, "It is against the law for you to take her."
Herod wanted to kill John. But he was afraid of the people, because they thought that John was a prophet.
On Herod's birthday, Herodias's daughter danced for Herod and his guests. She pleased Herod very much.
So he promised her by an oath that he would give her everything she asked for.
Her mother told her what to say. The girl said to Herod: "Give me the head of John the Baptist on a large platter."
The king was very upset. But he remembered his promise and his dinner guests. So he ordered one of his men to give her what she asked for.
Herod beheaded John in prison.
His head was brought on a large plate and given to the girl. Then she carried it to her mother.
The disciples of John came and took his body and buried it. Then they went and told Jesus. Jesus feeds the five thousand
Jesus heard what had happened to John. He wanted to be alone. So he went by boat to a quiet place. The crowd heard about it. They followed him on foot from the towns.
When Jesus reached the shore, he saw a large crowd. He felt deep concern for them. He healed their sick.
As evening approached, the disciples came to him. They said, "There is nothing here. It is already late. Send the crowds away so they can go and buy some food in the villages."
Jesus answered, "They do not need to go away. You give them something to eat."
They said: "We have only five loaves of bread and two fish."
"Bring them to me," he said.
Then Jesus directed the people to sit on the grass. He took the five loaves and two fish. He lifted his eyes to heaven and gave thanks. He broke the loaves into pieces. Then he gave them to the disciples. And the disciples gave them to the people.
They all ate and were full. The students collected 12 baskets of the remaining pieces.
The number of men who ate was about 5,000. Women and children also ate. Jesus walks on water.
Immediately Jesus made the disciples get into the boat. He commanded them to go ahead of him to the other side of the Sea of Galilee. Then he sent the crowd away.
After sending them off, he climbed up the side of a mountain alone to pray. And when evening came, he was there alone.
The boat was already far from the shore. The waves were hitting it hard because the wind was blowing against it.
Early in the morning, Jesus went out to the disciples. He walked on the lake.
They saw him walking on the lake and got scared. They said, "It's a ghost!" and screamed in fear.
Immediately Jesus called out to them, saying, "Take courage! It is I. Do not be afraid."
Peter said, "Lord, is it you?" He said to him, "If it is I, tell me to come to you on the water."
Jesus said, "Come." So Peter got out of the boat. He walked on the water toward Jesus.
But when Peter saw the wind, he was afraid. He began to sink. He cried out, "Lord! Save me!"
Immediately Jesus reached out his hand and caught him. He said, "You have such little faith! Why did you doubt me?"
When they boarded the boat, the wind calmed.
Then those in the boat worshiped Jesus. They said, "Truly you are the Son of God!"
They crossed the lake and landed at Gennesaret.
The men who were living there got to know Jesus. So they sent a message to all the surrounding regions. People brought all their sick to Jesus.
They pleaded with him to let those who were sick only touch the edge of his garment. And everyone who touched him was healed.
What makes people "impure"?
Some of the Pharisees and some teachers of the law came from Jerusalem to see Jesus. They asked,
Why dont your students obey what the sheikhs teach? Your students do not wash their hands before they eat!
Jesus answered, "And why do you not obey God's command? Instead, you prefer to follow your own teachings!
God said: "Honor your father and your mother." (Exodus 20:12; Deuteronomy 5:16) He also said: "Whoever curses his father or his mother shall be put to death." (Exodus 21:17; Leviticus 20:9)
But you allow people to say to their parents: "Any help you have received from us is a gift dedicated to God."
They do not need to honor their parents with their gift. You make the word of God of no effect by your tradition.
O demonstrators! Isaiah was right when he prophesied about you. He said,
These people honor me with their words, but their hearts are far from me.
"Their worship means nothing to me. They only know human rules." (Isaiah 29:13)
Jesus called the crowd to him. He said, "Listen and understand.
What enters your mouth does not make you "unclean." Rather, what comes out of your mouth is what makes you "unclean."
Then the disciples came to him. They asked, "Do you know that the Pharisees were angry when they heard this?"
Jesus answered, "There are plants that my Father in heaven did not plant. They will be uprooted.
Leave them. The Pharisees are blind leaders. If a blind man leads another blind man, both will fall into a pit.
Peter said, "Explain this to us."
Jesus asked them, "Do you still not understand?"
Don't you see? Everything that enters the mouth goes to the stomach. Then it leaves the body.
But what comes out of the mouth comes from the heart. Those are the things that make you "unclean."
Evil thoughts come from the heart. Likewise, murder, adultery, and other sexual sins. Also theft, false testimony, and lying to others.
Those are the things that make you "unclean." But eating without washing your hands does not make you "unclean." "The Faith of a Canaanite Woman"
Jesus left Galilee and went to the region of Tyre and Sidon.
There was a woman from Canaan living near Tyre and Sidon. She came to him and cried out, "Lord! Son of David! Have mercy on me! A demon is controlling my daughter. She is suffering greatly."
Jesus did not say a single word. His disciples approached him and pleaded, "Send her away. She keeps crying out after us."
Jesus answered, "I was sent only to the people of Israel. They are like lost sheep."
Then the woman fell to her knees before him. "Oh Lord! Help me!" she said.
He answered, "It is not right to take the children's bread and throw it to their dogs."
"Yes, Lord," she said. "But even dogs eat the crumbs that fall from their masters' table."
Jesus answered, "Woman, you have great faith! It will be done for you as you wish." At that moment, her daughter was healed. Jesus feeds the four thousand
Jesus left that place. He walked along the Sea of Galilee. Then he went up the side of a mountain and sat down.
Large crowds gathered around him. They brought to him the blind and those who could not walk. They also brought the disabled, those who could not speak, and many others. They placed them at his feet, and he healed them.
People were amazed. Those who could not speak were speaking. Those who were disabled became healthy. Those who could not walk were walking. Those who were blind began to see. So the people praised the God of Israel.
Then Jesus called his disciples to come to him. He said, "I feel deep concern for these people. They have already been with me for three days. They have nothing to eat. I do not want to send them away hungry. If I do, they will become too weak on their way back home."
His disciples answered him, "There is nothing here," they said. "Where can we get enough bread to feed this large crowd?"
Jesus asked, "How many loaves do you have?" They answered, "Seven, and a little bit of small fish."
Jesus told the crowd to sit on the ground.
He took the seven loaves and the fish and gave thanks. Then he broke them and gave them to the disciples. The disciples distributed the food to the people.
They all ate and were satisfied. After that, the disciples gathered seven baskets of the leftover pieces.
The number of men who ate was 4,000. Women and children also ate.
After Jesus sent the crowd away, he got into the boat. He headed to the area near Magdala.
Jesus is asked for a miraculous sign
The Pharisees and the Sadducees came to test Jesus. They asked him to show them a miraculous sign from heaven.
He answered, "In the evening you look at the sky. You say, 'The weather will be good. The sky is red.'"
In the morning, she says: "Today will be stormy. The sky is red and full of clouds." You know the meaning of what you see in the sky. But you cannot understand the signs of what is happening now.
An evil and treacherous people ask for a miraculous sign. But they will be given only the sign of Jonah." Then Jesus left them and went away. The yeast of the Pharisees and Sadducees
The students crossed to the other side of the lake. They forgot to bring bread.
Jesus said to them, "Beware of the yeast of the Pharisees and Sadducees."
The students talked about this among themselves. They said, "He must be saying this because we didn't bring any bread."
Jesus knew what they were saying. He said to them, "You have such little faith! Why are you talking among yourselves about not having bread?
Don't you understand yet? Don't you remember the five loaves for the five thousand? Don't you remember how many baskets of pieces were gathered?
Do you not remember the seven loaves for the four thousand? Do you not remember how many baskets of pieces were gathered?
How can you not understand? I was not talking to you about bread. But beware of the yeast of the Pharisees and the Sadducees.
Then the disciples understood that Jesus was not telling them to beware of the yeast used in bread. Rather, He was warning them about what the Pharisees and Sadducees taught. Peter says that Jesus is the Christ.
Jesus went to the region of Caesarea Philippi. There he asked his disciples, "Who do people say the Son of Man is?"
They answered, "Some say John the Baptist; others say Elijah; and others say Jeremiah, or one of the prophets."
"But what about you?" he asked. "Who do you say I am?"
Simon Peter answered, "You are the Christ. You are the Son of the living God."
Jesus answered, "Blessed are you, Simon son of Jonah! For this was not revealed to you by any ordinary man. But my Father in heaven has revealed it to you.
This is what I tell you. You are Peter. On this rock I will build my church. The gates of hell will not be strong enough to destroy it.
I will give you the keys of the kingdom of heaven. Whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven. And whatever you loose on earth will be loosed in heaven.
Then Jesus warned his disciples not to tell anyone that he was the Messiah. Jesus speaks about his coming death.
Since then, Jesus began to explain to his disciples what would happen to him. He told them that he must go to Jerusalem. There he would have to suffer many things from the elders, the chief priests, and the teachers of the law. He must be killed, and on the third day, he will rise from the dead.
Peter took Jesus aside and began to rebuke him. He said, "Never, Lord! This will never happen to you!"
Jesus turned and said to Peter, "Get behind me, Satan! You are a stumbling block to me. You do not have in mind the things of God, but the things of men."
Then Jesus spoke to his disciples. He said: "If anyone wants to follow me, he must deny himself. He must take up his cross and follow me.
If anyone wants to save his life, he will lose it. But if he loses his life for my sake, he will find it.
What good is it for a man to gain the whole world, yet lose himself? Or what can a man give in exchange for his soul?
The Son of Man will come in the glory of His Father. His angels will come with Him. And He will reward each one according to what he has done.
What I am about to tell you is true. Some of those standing here will not die before they see the Son of Man coming in his kingdom.
The change of Jesus' appearance
After six days Jesus took Peter, James, and John the brother of James with him. He led them up a high mountain. They were completely alone.
There is before them a change in his appearance. His face shone like the sun. His clothes became white as light.
At that moment, Moses and Elijah appeared before them. Moses and Elijah were talking with Jesus.
Peter said to Jesus: "Lord, it is good for us to be here. If you wish, I will set up three shelters. One for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah."
While Peter was still speaking, a bright cloud surrounded them. A voice came from the cloud: "This is my Son, whom I love. I am very pleased with him. Listen to him!"
When the students heard this, they were terrified. They fell face down on the ground.
But Jesus came and touched them. He said, "Get up, do not be afraid."
When they looked up, they saw no one but Jesus.
They came down from the mountain. On the way down, Jesus told them what to do. "Do not tell anyone what you have seen," he said. "Wait until the Son of Man is raised from the dead."
The disciples asked him, "Why do the teachers of the law say that Elijah must come first?"
Jesus answered, "That is correct. Elijah is supposed to come and make all things new again.
But I tell you, Elijah has already come. People did not recognize him. They did to him everything they wanted to do. In the same way, they will make the Son of Man suffer.
Then the disciples understood that Jesus was talking to them about John the Baptist. Jesus heals a boy who was possessed by a demon.
When they approached the crowd, a man came up to Jesus. He knelt before him on his knees.
He said: "O Lord, have mercy on my son. He is trembling severely and suffering greatly. He often falls into fire or water.
"I brought him to your disciples. But they could not heal him."
Jesus said: "O unbelieving and wicked people! How long shall I be with you? How long shall I endure you? Bring the boy to me."
Jesus commanded the demon to come out of the boy, and it came out. He was healed at that very moment.
Then the disciples came to Jesus privately. They asked him, "Why couldn't we cast out the demon?"
He answered: "Because your faith is very small. What I am telling you is true. If you have faith the size of a mustard seed, that is enough. You can say to this mountain, 'Move from here to there.' And it will move. Nothing will be impossible for you."
